### Cursor AI Execution Rules (add-on)

No hard-coded dates or parameters
 Always use variables/place-holders (e.g. {{start_date}}, {{month}}, {{plan_type}}). Prompt the user for any value that is not supplied.

Respect existing code-base structure
 Never create new folders or top-level files unless explicitly requested. Re-use or extend modules already present.

Produce functions, not stand-alone scripts
 Wrap every new routine inside a callable function located in the correct domain module. Avoid procedural one-off scripts.

Centralize shared utilities
 If a helper is reusable, place it in the existing utils / services folder instead of the feature file that first needs it.

Avoid single-use .py files
 For exploratory work prefer notebooks, SQL in /queries, or Airflow/DBT jobs. Only commit production code.

Check Mixpanel Lexicon before adding tracking
 Never duplicate an event or property that already exists in the Mixpanel dictionary.

Default output formatting to Argentina standards
 Currency symbol “$”, decimal separator “,”, thousand separator “.” in every CSV, XLSX or chart produced.

Attach metadata to every metric export
 Include: date range, data source, record count, and filters used.

Make every report parametrizable
 Scripts must accept start_date, end_date, segment, and output_path; default output path only after user confirmation.

Protect secrets and .env integrity
 Read credentials from existing env vars or vault; never overwrite .env without explicit confirmation.

Log reusable insights
 Optionally append strategic findings to Insights.md with a #tag for future reference.

Suggest automation on repetitive requests
 If the same report is generated more than three times in 30 days, prompt the user to schedule or pipeline it.

Maximum file length 300 lines
 When a file exceeds this size, propose a refactor and split responsibility.

Unit tests first for any new function touching core finance or billing logic
 Tests must cover happy path and one failure path at minimum.

Mock data only inside test suites
 Never introduce stubs or fake data in development or production code.

Default measurement system: metric
 Distances, weights, and volumes must use SI units.

When a placeholder KPI already exists in dashboards, link to it instead of rebuilding the visualization.

Cursor must prompt before storing any non-public customer data outside approved databases.

Use semver-compliant version bumps in package__init__.py whenever a public interface changes.

Always include an inline docstring explaining purpose, inputs, outputs, and side effects for every new function.


